bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=caledhontelrana>Caledhon TelRana</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I read boards more<br>than I play EQ....</span><br>  Posts: 668<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/24/03 10:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=448.topic&index=63>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: &quot;Morality is not relative.&quot;</span><hr size=1> Wolvar, try to at least be coherent if you're going to post something.<br>
<br>
Shehbahn - <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.friends-of-tibet.org.nz/tibet.html">www.friends-of-tibet.org.nz/tibet.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
That's a lot of bloodshed for peace-loving Buddhists.<br>
<br>
Tuwene, we can argue about the influence of religion on the development of western culture later =)  I will only point out that Christian influence, and the Catholic Church in particular, was absolutely essential to not only the Renaissance, but the development of basically every Western thinker there is.  It's a complex deal, but at any rate the road (or Roman Via?) there isn't what I'm interested in... where we are now is.<br>
<br>
I've said it before, but I'll say it again... we've switched topics here.  I'm not talking about &quot;morality&quot; any more, I'm talking about ideas and the very broad concept of civic culture.  I'm not saying that Christian values are superior to Buudhist values because of relative prosperity.  The ideas I'm talking about are not peculariarly Christian at all, except in that they were refined and implemented by Christians and Deists in their final forms - that of the Western democracy.  I do believe that, despite this, they are exportable to any culture, including that of Iraq, which was brought us to this whole debate in the first place.<br>
<br>
The superiority thing comes into play here - I am willing to state broadly that Western style democracies are superior to all other forms of government.  This obviously covers a lot of ground, and leaves a lot of room for shifting around here and there; there are many implementations of Western style democracy.  Sometimes the system fails, too.  When this occurs, however, it is most often due to a lack of trust in the system and a loss of legitimacy for whatever reason.  The root cause, then?  Insufficient civic culture, insufficient public faith in the root ideals of democracy.  So the problem is, how do you reinforce these ideals?  How can a culture be changed to value Western ideas and foster democracy?<br>
<br>
This is not a radical viewpoint.  There are hundreds of academic papers on the topic, and I've even read a few of them.  Any political scientist who isn't an outright Communist will easily tell you that democracy is the theoretically best system of government for any nation.  I say theoretically because not every democratizing nation is going to have the benefit of the United States as its direct patron like Iraq (hopefully) will, and therefore sometimes democracy is simply not feasible immediately.  The problem lies in getting it to work properly, and the reason it sometimes might not work is that the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>people don't believe in it, or its underlying ideas</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.<br>
<br>
So I agree with you, Shehbahn, that Iraq is going to be a mess of a place when Saddam is gone.  Where I disagree with you is in your assumption that it will never get fixed.  It is not only in Iraq's best interest to adopt a democracy, it is in ours.  Think of it as a reverse domino effect - Saudi Arabia and Iran do, for sure.  If we can demonstrate that democracy in an Arabic Islamic Middle Eastern state can work, and that we are willing to give our support to such states as they transition, then I think people will begin to support us more and more.  People like being free, after all.  Ask any Iraqi.  The trick is going to be in getting it set up in the first place.  With Turkey as a model, and with her support behind us, and given enough effort on our part, I think democracy in Iraq can happen... and once it does, that alone will strike a bigger blow against Islamic fundamentalist terrorism than any hundred or thousand of bombs or raids.  We're going to have an enormous groundswell of support from the Iraqi people once we free them, and if we don't squander it with 5 years of military government, but instead immediately do our utmost to forge an Iraqi-lead democratic government and then support it <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>for as long as it takes</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, it can be done.  For the good of Iraq, the U.S., and the entire world.<br>
<br>
 <p>Caledhon TelRana - Champion<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=51701"><br>
Vethantis Soulbonker</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> - Phantasmist<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Revolution</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
