<br>
They seem to accept it right now.  Saddam's claims to be the Defender of the Faithful are as obviously laughable to Muslims as they are to us.  Besides, read what I said about Turkey - they claim that democracy need not necessarily mean 100% separation of church and state.  I think this is problematic, but if it means that democratization, however imperfect, is possible, I am all for it.  Call it an intermediary step, but it's a huge step in the right direction.<br>
<br>
Go look up the term &quot;consociational democracy&quot;.  That's just one of the many ideas for dealing with the exact problem you describe.  It's not as hopeless as that.<br>
<br>
&quot;This is no &quot;trick&quot; - you can't force a national identity where there is no ethnic common ground ! The soviets tried it - look at what happened in Jugoslavia. The minute the red army left, the place imploded and is now divided again along ethnic boundaries.&quot;<br>
<br>
On the contrary.<br>
<br>
Yugoslavia was pulled together by Tito, and his personal leadership kept it together.  Interestingly, many of his programs to re-educate Yugoslavs into thinking of themselves as Yugoslavs rather than Bosnians, Serbs, Croats, etc. worked somewhat.  A large part of the reason why they did not had to do with the corrupt Communist government which was in place and the tendency for the best and brightest to flee the country to try and build a better life elsewhere.  The fact remains, however, that significant numbers *were* beginning to identify with the new state.<br>
<br>
Things went wrong when, after Tito's death, the Serbs began a campaign to dominate the nation, led by Milosevic.  Without his enormous ambition and heavyhanded repression, and given significant reforms, it is very possible that Yugoslavia could have remained a perfectly viable nation.  If only Tito had died 10 years later.  If only the Communist Party leaders had actually tried to work together rather than Milosevic trumpeting a new Serb domination and forcing a new fracturing of identity... the problems began not in the 1990s, but in the 1980s.  Who can say how it would have gone had a nation like the U.S. been there to guide them?  If there had actually been free elections after Tito's death, rather than the old corrupt Communist Party bosses sharing power in an inadequate rotational system and vying for resources that were shared and distributed (somewhat) fairly by Tito?<br>
<br>
National leaders can make an enormous difference.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yeah - Turkey is a model... riiiight. They follow in lockstep right behind NK in human rights abuse.&quot;<br>
<br>
What are you referring to?  The WWI Ottoman-era Armenian massacre?  That's old news, Shehbahn.  You might as well accuse Bush of human rights abuses because of the Trail of Tears.<br>
<br>
Note that I never claimed Turkey was perfect, of course.  Their freedom of the press is suspect, and they are not a &quot;model democracy&quot; by any means, but they are an Islamic nation which is also a democracy, and one which manages to survive just fine without being bombed by radical fundamentalists over its status as such.<br>
<br>
No, I didn't catch the oil field thing.  Are they asking for an actual territorial cession, or just the rights to them?  At any rate, I think it's a very minor point in the larger view of things.<br>
<br>
&quot;You think that all the terrorist wanna-be's are going to be sitting by and watching you trying to build your puppet toy democracy?&quot;<br>
<br>
Not all of them, no.  But I'm not talking short term.  The bin Laden types will be blowing things, but don't they do that anyway?  I didn't say it was going to be easy, but if we let ourselves be intimidated by the threat of terrorism, haven't the terrorists just won anyway?<br>
<br>
&quot;Just look at Israel : not two days without bodies coming in plastic bags. Yeah... the Israeli feel really free with their democracy right now within their 30 feet walls and tanks patrolling the streets.&quot;<br>
<br>
Jews are still flocking into Israel.  It's still prosperous, and free.  The tanks are patrolling the streets in the West Bank, not Jerusalem.  So, your point?  Besides, Iraqis are not Jews.  There is nowhere near the same hatred.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Uh huh - and there will be manna raining from the sky too!&quot;<br>
<br>
You disagree?  Show me an article, a news piece, anything where Iraqis not under duress from Saddam state that they don't want regime change.  Just saying &quot;Their culture says we hate the U.S.&quot; isn't good enough.  We're going into a nation that has been starved, tortured, mistreated, and misruled on a grand scale.  And you think that as soon as we arrive they will all rise up and cry, &quot;The Great Satan is here!!  We must fight!!&quot;?  I guess that's why Iraqi soldiers surrendered en masse in the first Gulf War, and why Iraqis were begging us to finish the job, just as they are now...<br>
<br>
