<br>
First, what is a culture?<br>
<br>
Am I a culture?  Are two people a culture? Would you say that your family is a culture?  Your school?  Your town?  Your state?  Your region (Midwest for example)?  Your nation?<br>
<br>
Can you belong to more than one culture at once?<br>
<br>
Can I just decide to be part of this culture one day and that culture the next as long as it suites my needs?<br>
<br>
If morality is dependant upon culture and you recognize this is entirely subjective then how do you justify questioning or passing judgment on another culture's morals? After-all it is all relative so their ways are no better or worse than yours.<br>
<br>
This philosophy seems to contradict itself since it relies on universal tolerance yet simultaneously argues against any universal norms. <br>
<br>
It also rules out any basis for judging horrendous crimes that are sanctioned by the standards of the culture or era (such as the Holocaust).<br>
<br>
It eliminates a place for cultural reformers since they would be opposing the accepted moral standard without basis.  Martin Luther King, for instance, would be the immoral one for opposing racial inequality. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wolvar>Wolvar</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_thatch.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>My third character is Lovawr</span><br>  Posts: 1676<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/25/03 11:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=448.topic&index=73>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: &quot;Morality is not relative.&quot;</span><hr size=1> You can question another culture's morales all you like.  How does questioning the morales of another culture make you the immoral one??  Questioning is not immoral.  Cultures can be wrong and/or divided on certain issues as well.  None of it is cut and dried.  We've seen evidence of a young culture learning slowly that racism is immoral.  So I don't understand why you think questioning something is immoral.<br>
